name: Yvonne Strahovski
description:
Yvonne Strahovski is an Australian actress, known for her roles as Serena Waterford in The Handmaid's Tale and as Miranda Lawson in the videogames series Mass Effect, among many other important roles.

This TI has been updated. Please check the "About this version" section for more info.

Note: There is a fantastic LoRA of Yvonne Strahovski (not Strahovsky! :D), created by @stablediffusionbox936, also available in this site, if you prefer that to embeddings. You can find it here.

modelVersions.name: v3.0
modelVersions.description:
Retrained once again from scratch. My process has changed quite a lot since I first tried Yvonne's TI. For instance, I still upscaled pictures back then, which I'm now sure had a pretty negative effect on the embeddings.

This one is a (yet again) 1000-step TI, trained on a dataset of 20 images with my usual settings.

modelVersions.name: v2.1
modelVersions.description:
I decided to keep training the previous embedding and running tests every 100 steps or so. I already felt the TI was close to overtraining at 400 steps, but sometimes it's hard to judge just how close it really is. As far as I can tell, at 850, this one is definitely overtrained, even if just slightly, but I'm uploading it cause I've noticed clear improvements. The saturation is easy to get rid of, and I've obtained really good results with "(str4h0vski:0.99)" in my red carpet prompt (which is my usual go-to prompt for testing purposes).

That said, I'll probably stop updating this TI now, at least for some time. Hope you enjoy it!

modelVersions.name: v2.0
modelVersions.description:
Retrained from scratch after pruning a few images. I think the results are more accurate than in the previous version, also a bit more consistent, but let's see what you all think. It definitely feels that the embedding shines at close range, not so much at wider shots. That may be a consequence of the dataset I chose, so maybe I'll try to address that in the future.

The TI seems already a bit overtrained at 400 steps. As usual, in case you're getting saturated images with a given prompt, try reducing the embedding weight (0.99 should already solve the issue in many cases). And if you need help building a working prompt, just follow the examples I'm posting or let me know ih the comments!
